48
00:02:13,077 --> 00:02:14,920
So we had a theory.

49
00:02:16,274 --> 00:02:19,795
we're gonna try to combine the idea of mentally engaging

50
00:02:19,795 --> 00:02:23,837
our players with emotionally engaging our players.

51
00:02:23,837 --> 00:02:25,057
Not just grabbing them by their mind,

52
00:02:25,057 --> 00:02:26,277
but grabbing them by their gut,

53
00:02:26,277 --> 00:02:28,078
grabbing them by their heart.

54
00:02:28,078 --> 00:02:31,359
And not separately in different beats of the game,

55
00:02:31,359 --> 00:02:33,700
but together and hopefully all the time.

56
00:02:33,700 --> 00:02:36,601
So as we go through this talk,

57
00:02:36,601 --> 00:02:37,941
I'd like you guys to ask yourself

58
00:02:37,941 --> 00:02:40,222
constantly three questions.

59
00:02:40,222 --> 00:02:42,403
One is, how are we experiencing

60
00:02:42,403 --> 00:02:43,523
the things we are looking at?

61
00:02:44,785 --> 00:02:47,529
How do we gauge that experience?

62
00:02:47,529 --> 00:02:51,294
And why are we feeling it the way we're feeling it?

63
00:02:51,294 --> 00:02:53,877
Once we figure out the how and the why,

64
00:02:53,877 --> 00:02:55,779
let's try to figure out what we can do about it

65
00:02:55,779 --> 00:02:59,203
in order to kind of utilize it,

66
00:02:59,203 --> 00:03:01,126
in order to push that engagement experience.

67
00:03:03,027 --> 00:03:05,370
So let's look at what we have out the gate in games.

68
00:03:05,370 --> 00:03:08,313
We have a superpower, and that is mental absorption.

69
00:03:08,313 --> 00:03:12,918
Most of the mechanics we have from the last amazing 20 years

70
00:03:12,918 --> 00:03:17,903
or so of game design is the ability to suck the viewer in

71
00:03:17,903 --> 00:03:18,404
to the content.

72
00:03:18,404 --> 00:03:20,606
And that is a very mental experience.

73
00:03:21,731 --> 00:03:24,834
So if we look at some of the standard mechanics

74
00:03:24,834 --> 00:03:28,198
we have in games these days is navigation exploration,

75
00:03:28,198 --> 00:03:31,061
it's a big boon to absorption, getting us sucked in.

76
00:03:31,061 --> 00:03:33,243
We have puzzles and other engaging mechanics,

77
00:03:33,243 --> 00:03:34,725
it's a big boon to absorption.

78
00:03:34,725 --> 00:03:37,748
We have combat, that's a big mental absorbing parameter.

79
00:03:37,748 --> 00:03:39,830
But we also have story.

80
00:03:40,658 --> 00:03:44,842
And story allows us to engage the viewer in a bit more of a sympathetic way.

81
00:03:44,842 --> 00:03:49,306
And before we move on, let's talk about the difference between sympathy and empathy.

82
00:03:49,306 --> 00:03:51,908
It's going to be critical for the remainder of this talk.

83
00:03:51,908 --> 00:03:57,813
Sympathy is our ability to feel something for somebody else.

84
00:03:57,813 --> 00:04:00,456
It's a feeling for them experience.

85
00:04:00,456 --> 00:04:05,800
Empathy is our ability to get engaged with somebody else's emotion, but actually feel

86
00:04:05,800 --> 00:04:08,122
it as myself, as us, as we.

87
00:04:09,133 --> 00:04:13,037
It's a personal versus an external experience.

88
00:04:13,037 --> 00:04:19,865
The tricky thing with empathy is, at least we found, that you can't engage empathy directly.

89
00:04:19,865 --> 00:04:24,189
It's an amalgamation of different parameters coming together, and we'll get to that in

90
00:04:24,189 --> 00:04:24,930
a little bit.

91
00:04:27,358 --> 00:04:33,279
So we are trying to take absorption and combine it with sympathy to create a sense of empathetic

92
00:04:33,279 --> 00:04:39,661
immersion, a sense you are truly, really there in the content, experiencing it as yourself,

93
00:04:39,661 --> 00:04:43,662
both from a mental standpoint and from a sympathetic emotional standpoint.

94
00:04:43,662 --> 00:04:48,763
So how do we do this?

95
00:04:49,930 --> 00:04:52,574
How do we take absorption and combine it with sympathy?

96
00:04:52,574 --> 00:04:56,720
And not only that, how do we do that in a uniform enough manner

97
00:04:56,720 --> 00:05:00,084
that we can stay consistent within this entwinement

98
00:05:00,084 --> 00:05:04,671
and maintain critical mass to have that sense of empathetic immersion

99
00:05:04,671 --> 00:05:06,333
throughout the entire experience?

100
00:05:07,582 --> 00:05:11,245
So let's go back to some traditional approaches to how to tell visual stories and how to tell

101
00:05:11,245 --> 00:05:15,069
emotionally engaging moments. We'll look at the first person camera, the third person

102
00:05:15,069 --> 00:05:22,656
camera, more traditional styles. If any of you guys have motion sickness, beware.

103
00:05:41,548 --> 00:05:43,769
Cool. So let's ask ourselves, how do we feel about this?

104
00:05:43,769 --> 00:05:46,550
I definitely felt that was me, right?

105
00:05:46,550 --> 00:05:48,451
I was the protagonist.

106
00:05:48,451 --> 00:05:50,272
That was really immersive.

107
00:05:50,272 --> 00:05:52,112
I was very absorbed.

108
00:05:52,112 --> 00:05:54,893
