109
00:05:54,893 --> 00:05:56,614
There was no emotional connection for me.

110
00:05:56,614 --> 00:05:58,435
There was no sympathy.

111
00:05:58,435 --> 00:06:00,376
And if you guys noticed, the protagonist was

112
00:06:00,376 --> 00:06:03,817
pushing their hand forward towards their female counterpart

113
00:06:03,817 --> 00:06:06,398
trying to say something, but they didn't speak.

114
00:06:06,398 --> 00:06:07,679
And we'll get to why in a moment,

115
00:06:07,679 --> 00:06:09,199
but that's actually a critical distinction

116
00:06:09,199 --> 00:06:11,000
that's a very big problem with a first-person camera.

117
00:06:12,280 --> 00:06:35,036
Let's take a look at a third-person camera and see how that makes us feel.

118
00:06:46,378 --> 00:06:52,303
Cool. So I definitely felt for them, right? There were characters in front of me, I felt for their experience,

119
00:06:52,303 --> 00:06:57,527
sympathy was definitely evoked in me, but I wasn't there. I was kind of like a fly on the wall,

120
00:06:57,527 --> 00:07:05,033
experiencing this whole thing through my mind's eye. So while I did have sympathy, I got a really

121
00:07:05,033 --> 00:07:08,276
big dip and deficit in my absorption. So there's a problem here, right?

122
00:07:09,038 --> 00:07:14,223
The first-person camera has the problem where we engage so deeply in that point of view

123
00:07:14,223 --> 00:07:18,707
that we can't have the protagonist speak or it feels like the words are being inserted

124
00:07:18,707 --> 00:07:19,408
into our brain.

125
00:07:19,408 --> 00:07:23,011
And the first thing we do is we pop out of the experience.

126
00:07:23,011 --> 00:07:25,794
We get a sense of mental and emotional dissonance.

127
00:07:25,794 --> 00:07:29,056
So we can't really tell a deep emotional story in first-person camera.

128
00:07:30,217 --> 00:07:32,138
Third person, while it's really empathetic, sorry,

129
00:07:32,138 --> 00:07:34,660
sympathetic, it's not absorbing enough.

130
00:07:34,660 --> 00:07:36,901
So we can't actually get to sympathy

131
00:07:36,901 --> 00:07:38,382
with a traditional third person camera.

132
00:07:38,382 --> 00:07:42,425
So how do we push absorption onto the third person camera

133
00:07:42,425 --> 00:07:44,106
to create a sense of empathy?

134
00:07:44,106 --> 00:07:47,889
So our theory was this.

135
00:07:48,977 --> 00:07:51,520
Instead of thinking of it as a first-person camera and a third-person camera,

136
00:07:51,520 --> 00:07:54,062
we're going to try to design from an emotional standpoint

137
00:07:54,062 --> 00:07:56,805
something like a first-and-a-half-person camera.

138
00:07:56,805 --> 00:08:02,010
We're going to try to use the third person, but bring the experience from them to me.

139
00:08:02,010 --> 00:08:07,556
In a sense, combining absorption and sympathy to create a sense of empathetic immersion,

140
00:08:07,556 --> 00:08:13,222
a sense that you are truly there, engaging as yourself or as part of the team.

141
00:08:16,150 --> 00:08:19,576
As we were experimenting with this state of empathetic immersion,

142
00:08:19,576 --> 00:08:23,381
we're starting to kind of sputter with successes and get a general idea of

143
00:08:23,381 --> 00:08:26,787
maybe where this can go. We realized how

144
00:08:26,787 --> 00:08:28,269
fragile the state is.

145
00:08:29,347 --> 00:08:32,048
It's kind of like running around with an egg on a spoon.

146
00:08:32,048 --> 00:08:35,310
It's really easy to get a really small bump on your spoon

147
00:08:35,310 --> 00:08:36,391
and drop that egg.

148
00:08:36,391 --> 00:08:37,852
The moment that egg is dropped,

149
00:08:37,852 --> 00:08:39,433
it's very hard to reconstruct it,

150
00:08:39,433 --> 00:08:40,514
put it back on the spoon

151
00:08:40,514 --> 00:08:43,436
and re-engage within that same experience.

152
00:08:43,436 --> 00:08:45,997
But just because we come in with this superpower

153
00:08:45,997 --> 00:08:48,079
out of the gate with our sense of deep absorption,

154
00:08:48,079 --> 00:08:50,040
with interactive media,

155
00:08:50,040 --> 00:08:51,401
we have the potential to be probably

156
00:08:51,401 --> 00:08:55,043
one of the most powerful mediums for engaging storytelling.

157
00:08:55,043 --> 00:08:58,205
So how does all this relate to God of War?

158
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:02,063
God of War starts with a big problem.

159
00:09:02,063 --> 00:09:03,284
It's steeped in fantasy.

160
00:09:03,284 --> 00:09:06,687
In essence, it says, I am unreality.

161
00:09:06,687 --> 00:09:14,133
We have dragons, we have orcs, we have ogres, we have people that can lift mountains.

162
00:09:14,133 --> 00:09:15,274
That's nothing we can relate to.

163
00:09:16,538 --> 00:09:21,781
And as we were studying that sense of absorption, that sense of being sucked into the content,

164
00:09:21,781 --> 00:09:26,904
we realized that our ability to relate to our environment as something that we recognize

165
00:09:26,904 --> 00:09:31,446
is critical for us to actually be absorbed in the content.

166
00:09:31,446 --> 00:09:33,006
So what we can do?

167
00:09:33,006 --> 00:09:34,147
It's got a bit of a problem.

168
00:09:34,147 --> 00:09:40,530
We tried to find another visual language that has the exact opposite problem that we do.

169
00:09:40,530 --> 00:09:43,952
In this case, it wasn't actually a problem, it was a blessing.

170
00:09:43,952 --> 00:09:45,773
We found the documentary style, actually.

171
00:09:46,539 --> 00:09:50,109
kind of calculate the documentary style for ourselves.

172
00:09:50,109 --> 00:09:52,055
The documentary style has.

173
00:09:52,945 --> 00:09:56,969
the visual approach of telling us that it is speaking the truth.

174
00:09:56,969 --> 00:10:00,952
We are used to seeing it tell things that are true,

175
00:10:00,952 --> 00:10:04,035
that are real, that are relatable.

176
00:10:04,035 --> 00:10:06,016
So in essence, we get a double boon.

177
00:10:06,016 --> 00:10:08,118
We get a grounded experience,

178
00:10:08,118 --> 00:10:10,640
which we're used to seeing from documentary footage,

179
00:10:10,640 --> 00:10:15,384
but we also get a very character-relevant story

180
00:10:15,384 --> 00:10:17,066
that is character-based,

181
00:10:17,066 --> 00:10:20,088
which we're used to seeing documentary stylists use.

182
00:10:20,909 --> 00:10:24,051
So what we're trying to create is a sense of believable fantasy.

183
00:10:24,051 --> 00:10:29,714
A sense that, yes, what I'm watching around me might not be as relatable,

184
00:10:29,714 --> 00:10:30,414
but I believe it.

185
00:10:30,414 --> 00:10:32,035
So all of us here, I will take a wager that all of us here,

186
00:10:32,035 --> 00:10:36,637
can hear with our eyes many different types of film language.

187
00:10:36,637 --> 00:10:42,581
It's like growing up in a family that speaks a different language.

188
00:10:42,581 --> 00:10:46,703
You might not be able to speak the language, but when you hear it...

189
00:10:47,174 --> 00:10:48,835
you completely understand it.

190
00:10:48,835 --> 00:10:50,997
So we're leveraging that fact.

191
00:10:50,997 --> 00:10:54,039
What we're telling the viewer from a visual standpoint is,

192
00:10:54,039 --> 00:10:55,880
hey, this is real.

193
00:10:55,880 --> 00:10:59,582
We're calibrating their mindset to accept reality.

194
00:10:59,582 --> 00:11:01,203
And once their shields are down,

195
00:11:01,203 --> 00:11:03,465
those shields we discussed,

196
00:11:03,465 --> 00:11:04,686
then we hit them with a fantasy.

197
00:11:04,686 --> 00:11:08,548
And they take the fantasy in reference to reality.

198
00:11:08,548 --> 00:11:13,171
One of my favorite case studies for this

199
00:11:13,171 --> 00:11:14,372
was The Exorcist from 1973.

200
