00:27:44,316 --> 00:27:49,179
want to draw attention to the camera operation, so the zooms have to be completely invisible.

509
00:27:49,179 --> 00:27:53,822
What we ended up doing is breaking zooms into two utilities.

510
00:27:54,700 --> 00:27:59,023
Zooming for utility, meaning I have to go from one place to another, maybe a zoom will

511
00:27:59,023 --> 00:28:05,486
help me. And two, zooming for emotional impact and emotional content. So let's take an example

512
00:28:05,486 --> 00:28:11,049
for a zoom for utility here. This is going back to our 2016 demo. We already watched

513
00:28:11,049 --> 00:28:15,152
the scene. You guys probably didn't notice that we had a pretty crazy zoom here. Let's

514
00:28:15,152 --> 00:28:15,832
take a quick look.

515
00:28:15,832 --> 00:28:16,152
Oh boy.

516
00:28:24,381 --> 00:28:25,361
Oh, wait!

517
00:28:25,361 --> 00:28:28,323
I hope he didn't notice I had a big zoom in here.

518
00:28:28,323 --> 00:28:31,385
Um, what we did here,

519
00:28:31,385 --> 00:28:33,886
we used a really wide 24mm lens

520
00:28:33,886 --> 00:28:35,587
to exasperate that big impact

521
00:28:35,587 --> 00:28:38,709
when Kratos slams that troll into the ice.

522
00:28:38,709 --> 00:28:41,531
To get that drama, we need it from a wide-angle lens.

523
00:28:41,531 --> 00:28:44,532
But then we need it to be 20 feet behind action

524
00:28:44,532 --> 00:28:48,154
within probably a matter of a second and a half

525
00:28:48,154 --> 00:28:50,576
to get over the kid's shoulder when he draws the arrow.

526
00:28:51,821 --> 00:28:54,624
So what we did, we dollied the camera back

527
00:28:54,624 --> 00:28:57,787
as we were zooming in, which essentially maintained Kratos

528
00:28:57,787 --> 00:29:00,169
on screen in the same size he was,

529
00:29:00,169 --> 00:29:02,291
making you feel like there's no camera movement,

530
00:29:02,291 --> 00:29:05,374
while we're actually trucking the camera 20 feet back.

531
00:29:05,374 --> 00:29:07,877
Let's take a look at that again in slow motion.

532
00:29:07,877 --> 00:29:12,922
Look at how that environment in the background compresses

533
00:29:12,922 --> 00:29:15,284
as the camera zooms.

534
00:29:15,284 --> 00:29:16,585
We're 20 feet behind him.

535
00:29:19,456 --> 00:29:21,897
Now let's look at an emotional content zoom.

536
00:29:21,897 --> 00:29:25,738
In this scene, Kratos starts off his, you know,

537
00:29:25,738 --> 00:29:29,260
traditional, standard, mean, kind of tough dad.

538
00:29:29,260 --> 00:29:32,401
Very impersonal shot, 24 millimeter wide.

539
00:29:32,401 --> 00:29:35,162
And very quickly after that, we transition to Kratos

540
00:29:35,162 --> 00:29:38,964
having one of probably the only two intimate moments

541
00:29:38,964 --> 00:29:41,725
he has within the game, and that's gathering the ashes

542
00:29:41,725 --> 00:29:43,185
of his wife that he just cremated.

543
00:29:43,911 --> 00:29:46,412
We ended up pushing all the way to 120 millimeters

544
00:29:46,412 --> 00:29:50,573
to get that sense of intimacy and compressed internal space.

545
00:29:50,573 --> 00:29:53,994
This is actually the biggest zoom range we did in the game.

546
00:29:53,994 --> 00:29:56,935
What we also noticed is in order to hide a zoom,

547
00:29:56,935 --> 00:30:00,056
but still make it emotionally impactful,

548
00:30:00,056 --> 00:30:03,137
we can kinda slap it on some motion

549
00:30:03,137 --> 00:30:04,718
that the character does,

550
00:30:04,718 --> 00:30:07,258
utilizing the motion to convey the zoom.

551
00:30:07,258 --> 00:30:08,279
And if it's designed well,

552
00:30:08,279 --> 00:30:10,379
that motion also conveys what the character

553
00:30:10,379 --> 00:30:12,100
is emotionally going through.

554
00:30:12,100 --> 00:30:13,420
In this case, it's a walk from.

555
00:30:13,824 --> 00:30:19,029
his son after he dismisses his son to walking towards his wife's cremation site.

556
00:30:19,029 --> 00:30:21,072
Let's take a look at how that looks.

557
00:30:43,213 --> 00:30:46,214
And we're at 120 millimeters.

558
00:30:46,214 --> 00:30:51,075
And then, of course, we have to find our way back, right?

559
00:30:51,075 --> 00:30:52,116
But that's a different story.

560
00:30:52,116 --> 00:30:56,037
So approach to visual defects.

561
00:30:56,037 --> 00:30:59,958
We actually worked pretty hard to make our visuals look worse.

562
00:30:59,958 --> 00:31:03,660
The whole thing came from the problem of the uncanny valley.

563
00:31:03,660 --> 00:31:05,840
And for those of you who are not familiar with the uncanny valley,

564
00:31:06,569 --> 00:31:10,771
The traditional thought would say that if something looks better,

565
00:31:10,771 --> 00:31:12,432
then it looks more believable.

566
00:31:12,432 --> 00:31:15,734
Kind of like in a linear manner, the more believable, the more relatable.

567
00:31:15,734 --> 00:31:20,176
What actually happens is when something becomes very close to realistic,

568
00:31:20,176 --> 00:31:23,818
our psyche starts judging it in a very harsh manner.

569
00:31:23,818 --> 00:31:27,080
It looks for realism, and it finds all the defects.

570
00:31:27,080 --> 00:31:32,103
There is a giant dip in believability just before you hit photorealism.

571
00:31:33,003 --> 00:31:36,144
And because of the power of our game engine these days

572
00:31:36,144 --> 00:31:37,744
and our amazing tech render teams

573
00:31:37,744 --> 00:31:38,625
and our amazing art teams,

574
00:31:38,625 --> 00:31:42,206
we fell right in the middle of the uncanny valley.

575
00:31:42,206 --> 00:31:46,367
So what we try to do is go back to the documentary style

576
00:31:46,367 --> 00:31:50,728
and find things that we relate to as realistic footage

577
00:31:50,728 --> 00:31:53,409
and slap on top of the image to try to at least,

578
00:31:53,409 --> 00:31:57,070
if not completely skip over the uncanny valley,

579
00:31:57,070 --> 00:31:59,010
kind of make it less, more shallow, less deep.

580
00:32:01,290 --> 00:32:04,774
So we added film grain, we added handheld,

581
00:32:04,774 --> 00:32:07,116
we added crap hitting your lens all over the place,

582
00:32:07,116 --> 00:32:10,059
lens flare, chromatic aberration, we slipped on focus.

583
00:32:10,059 --> 00:32:14,124
All these things that if you were a filmmaker

584
00:32:14,124 --> 00:32:17,087
shooting live action, you would try at all costs to avoid.

585
00:32:18,018 --> 00:32:22,781
But what it did is again spike our brains and calibrate them

586
00:32:22,781 --> 00:32:26,844
toward a sense of realism and helped us skip over the

587
00:32:26,844 --> 00:32:30,887
uncanny valley and relate to the footage without pushing

588
00:32:30,887 --> 00:32:32,788
back against it and then having a giant dip in

589
00:32:32,788 --> 00:32:33,188
absorption.

590
00:32:33,188 --> 00:32:37,071
A quick note on that, having a very strong understanding on

591
00:32:37,071 --> 00:32:42,274
how lenses, real world lenses work, how film backs work, how

592
00:32:42,274 --> 00:32:43,695
photo sensors work.

593
00:32:44,133 --> 00:32:47,115
how images actually get created in what fashion

594
00:32:47,115 --> 00:32:49,557
allowed us to do this in a very realistic manner,

595
00:32:49,557 --> 00:32:52,118
not just by slapping some elements on the lens

596
00:32:52,118 --> 00:32:54,580
and on the screen in our case,

597
00:32:54,580 --> 00:32:56,562
and hoping to achieve a sense of realism.

598
00:32:56,562 --> 00:32:58,843
So our approach to handheld,

599
00:32:58,843 --> 00:33:02,085
that was a big, big boon for us

600
00:33:02,085 --> 00:33:04,187
in terms of getting that raw absorption.

601
00:33:04,187 --> 00:33:07,069
I've heard a lot of people approach handheld

602
00:33:07,069 --> 00:33:11,032
as this kind of programmatic wobble on the screen,

603
00:33:11,032 --> 00:33:12,653
and nothing can be further from the truth.

604
00:33:13,630 --> 00:33:16,135
Each handheld has its own style.

605
00:33:16,135 --> 00:33:18,699
Not all handhelds are created equal.

606
00:33:18,699 --> 00:33:21,123
Sometimes blends of handhelds are needed

607
00:33:21,123 --> 00:33:23,547
in order to create a certain emotion

608
00:33:23,547 --> 00:33:24,929
and drive a certain sense.

609
00:33:27,097 --> 00:33:31,140
we actually went onto the mocap stage and shot our handhelds.

610
00:33:31,140 --> 00:33:35,263
On the bottom left here, you can see me in a mocap stage,

611
00:33:35,263 --> 00:33:39,466
well, the footage generated by me on a mocap stage,

612
00:33:39,466 --> 00:33:41,888
holding the camera and trying to keep it steady.

613
00:33:41,888 --> 00:33:45,491
On the far right, you can see me on a treadmill,

614
00:33:45,491 --> 00:33:50,014
jogging in a mocap studio, trying to keep my camera steady.

615
00:33:52,240 --> 00:33:55,901
to really get your handhelds to feel correct

616
00:33:55,901 --> 00:33:59,742
and really help bridge things like the uncanny valley

617
00:33:59,742 --> 00:34:02,723
or help calibrate the viewers into a documentary style.

618
00:34:02,723 --> 00:34:04,443
You have to treat them with the same amount

619
00:34:04,443 --> 00:34:05,964
of care and seriousness that you treat

620
00:34:05,964 --> 00:34:07,684
your character animations.

621
00:34:07,684 --> 00:34:13,986
What we did find is that handheld is incredibly nauseating.

622
00:34:13,986 --> 00:34:17,047
And as somebody who for the first six months

623
00:34:17,047 --> 00:34:19,127
of his work on God of War had Dramamine on his desk,

624
00:34:19,665 --> 00:34:24,607
I was very passionate about this.

625
00:34:24,607 --> 00:34:29,810
We had to figure out how to take our handheld wholesale

626
00:34:29,810 --> 00:34:32,391
and wrap it in some form of UI that allows the viewer

627
00:34:32,391 --> 00:34:35,112
to either calibrate it up or down to match

628
00:34:35,112 --> 00:34:38,413
their personal user experience, while still maintaining

629
00:34:38,413 --> 00:34:40,434
that emotional need that handheld provides

630
00:34:40,434 --> 00:34:41,635
from a documentary standpoint.

631
00:34:44,425 --> 00:34:51,168
What we also found is in order to diminish the nausea and diminish the motion a little bit,

632
00:34:51,168 --> 00:34:58,870
thinking of handheld from a rotational and translational standpoint separately was incredibly critical.

633
00:34:58,870 --> 00:35:05,172
The rotations controlled the movement of the world and how it bops up and down and around us,

634
00:35:05,172 --> 00:35:08,173
while the translations controlled the parallax of the foreground.

635
00:35:09,045 --> 00:35:11,885
Separating those two allowed us to massage the data,

636
00:35:11,885 --> 00:35:14,266
maintain it looking realistic,

637
00:35:14,266 --> 00:35:16,166
but lower its sense of nausea.

638
00:35:16,166 --> 00:35:20,727
So on the far left, we can see the raw jog motion

639
00:35:20,727 --> 00:35:21,627
that we shot on stage.

640
00:35:21,627 --> 00:35:25,788
On the center, you can see us blending it down a little bit

641
00:35:25,788 --> 00:35:28,509
with a combination of rotation and translation.

642
00:35:28,509 --> 00:35:31,349
And on the far right, you can see that actual data

643
00:35:31,349 --> 00:35:33,030
being applied to a jog in the game.

644
00:35:34,156 --> 00:35:36,897
What you'll also notice is that movement on the screen

645
00:35:36,897 --> 00:35:39,539
has a major factor to diminishing

646
00:35:39,539 --> 00:35:40,880
your perception of handheld.

647
00:35:40,880 --> 00:35:43,161
So that's something you have to account for

648
00:35:43,161 --> 00:35:44,762
when you're blending in your handheld data.

649
00:35:44,762 --> 00:35:51,065
So back to this design of the no cuts.

650
00:35:51,065 --> 00:35:52,826
Previs was critical.

651
00:35:52,826 --> 00:35:55,628
We previs-ed, revised it, previs-ed again.

652
00:35:55,628 --> 00:35:58,169
The idea is to make all your mistakes

653
00:35:58,169 --> 00:36:01,051
where it's fast and where it's cheap.

654
00:36:01,051 --> 00:36:02,952
Don't go on set and try to make your mistakes there.

655
00:36:04,473 --> 00:36:07,375
And also, you don't have to use super high-end methods

656
00:36:07,375 --> 00:36:12,399
of previs, like hand-key previs in 3D or rough mocap.

657
00:36:12,399 --> 00:36:15,081
Find the right element and style of previs

658
00:36:15,081 --> 00:36:17,183
you need in order to deliver what

659
00:36:17,183 --> 00:36:18,984
the shot needs to look like.

660
00:36:18,984 --> 00:36:19,965
Find your designs.

661
00:36:19,965 --> 00:36:20,806
Find your blocking.

662
00:36:20,806 --> 00:36:22,207
Find your staging.

663
00:36:22,207 --> 00:36:23,588
Find it quickly, and quickly enough

664
00:36:23,588 --> 00:36:24,909
for you to be able to iterate on it

665
00:36:24,909 --> 00:36:27,451
within the production timelines.

666
00:36:27,451 --> 00:36:31,374
And again, if you don't have previs, do not go on set.

667
00:36:31,374 --> 00:36:33,116
We did try that.

668
00:36:33,116 --> 00:36:33,556
It wasn't pretty.

669
00:36:35,799 --> 00:36:37,279
So let's take a look at a previous example.

670
00:36:37,279 --> 00:36:39,520
This was shot with a DSLR using a lens

671
00:36:39,520 --> 00:36:41,680
that roughly represented the focal lengths

672
00:36:41,680 --> 00:36:44,341
we were wanting for that specific scene.

673
00:36:44,341 --> 00:36:48,302
We shot this with our cinematic animation crew,

674
00:36:48,302 --> 00:36:52,123
Erica Pinto, Umberto Bossi, and Avieni.

675
00:36:52,123 --> 00:36:56,324
And I found that animators are great to work with,

676
00:36:56,324 --> 00:36:58,044
and they have a lot of fun doing it.

677
00:36:58,044 --> 00:36:58,724
I do as well.

678
00:36:58,724 --> 00:37:00,065
Let's take a look at how the scene looked.

679
00:37:06,826 --> 00:37:07,346
Your bow!

680
00:37:07,346 --> 00:37:07,486
Right!

681
00:37:07,486 --> 00:37:27,960
I'm glad you're okay.

682
00:37:47,200 --> 00:37:48,841
So again, working with your teammates is awesome.

683
00:37:48,841 --> 00:37:51,142
We had a lot of fun shooting this scene.

684
00:37:51,142 --> 00:37:54,523
We slapped it together, put it into After Effects

685
00:37:54,523 --> 00:37:57,084
just to get some lighting cues, some audio cues,

686
00:37:57,084 --> 00:37:59,105
just to find the mood of the scene.

687
00:37:59,105 --> 00:38:01,326
But we found exactly what we needed to do

688
00:38:01,326 --> 00:38:02,246
to make the scene work.

689
00:38:02,246 --> 00:38:04,047
We found the blocking, the staging,

690
00:38:04,047 --> 00:38:06,447
where to hide the zooms, how to stage the scene

691
00:38:06,447 --> 00:38:08,228
to properly emotionally deliver.

692
00:38:08,228 --> 00:38:10,989
So now let's see how it actually looked like in the game.

693
00:38:10,989 --> 00:38:11,269
Shoot.

694
00:38:11,269 --> 00:38:11,669
What was that?

695
00:38:11,669 --> 00:38:11,950
The ball.

696
00:38:49,264 --> 00:38:53,185
So, virtually identical, which is great.

697
00:38:53,185 --> 00:38:56,767
It means that we know what we're doing on set,

698
00:38:56,767 --> 00:38:59,447
we know how to design this ballet between the camera and the actors,

699
00:38:59,447 --> 00:39:02,148
what the actors need to be doing, what the camera needs to be doing,

700
00:39:02,148 --> 00:39:06,190
when, at what pacing, and we don't have to figure all that out on set,

701
00:39:06,190 --> 00:39:09,431
which makes shooting really, really, really comfortable.

702
00:39:09,431 --> 00:39:14,413
One thing to keep in mind, though, about, well, some things to keep in mind about Previs,

703
00:39:16,501 --> 00:39:23,402
If possible, at least for me, refrain from pre-vising in a three-dimensional software.

704
00:39:23,402 --> 00:39:30,784
That idea of needing to use a skill set in order to explore a shot already takes you

705
00:39:30,784 --> 00:39:33,184
one step away from cleanly exploring your concepts.

706
00:39:33,184 --> 00:39:39,146
If you can, explore all your scenes in your mind, draw them down in quick thumbnails,

707
00:39:39,146 --> 00:39:41,186
and then only go into the 3D software where

708
00:39:41,516 --> 00:39:43,696
you're trying to figure out if what you visualized

709
00:39:43,696 --> 00:39:44,337
actually works.

710
00:39:44,337 --> 00:39:47,337
I find I get much better and much more interesting results.

711
00:39:47,337 --> 00:39:52,158
Just because of the realism of game production,

712
00:39:52,158 --> 00:39:54,599
we don't always have the environments

713
00:39:54,599 --> 00:39:58,180
that we're going to shoot in ready when we need to shoot.

714
00:39:58,180 --> 00:40:02,901
So by all means, if you can, try avoiding that temptation

715
00:40:02,901 --> 00:40:03,981
of shooting generic.

716
00:40:04,797 --> 00:40:05,658
And what does generic mean?

717
00:40:05,658 --> 00:40:08,059
Oh, we'll just shoot or design or animate

718
00:40:08,059 --> 00:40:09,921
based on our characters,

719
00:40:09,921 --> 00:40:11,162
based on where the camera's gonna go,

720
00:40:11,162 --> 00:40:12,763
then we're just gonna take that whole thing

721
00:40:12,763 --> 00:40:14,204
and just plop it into an environment,

722
00:40:14,204 --> 00:40:14,824
it's gonna look great.

723
00:40:14,824 --> 00:40:15,685
It won't.

724
00:40:15,685 --> 00:40:19,007
You have to think about how the environment

725
00:40:19,007 --> 00:40:20,588
is gonna look like in your shot.

726
00:40:20,588 --> 00:40:21,949
You have to think about what your character's

727
00:40:21,949 --> 00:40:24,171
gonna be touching, where they're gonna be sitting.

728
00:40:24,171 --> 00:40:26,893
Without that level of interaction with your environment,

729
00:40:26,893 --> 00:40:28,274
your scenes are gonna be flat

730
00:40:28,274 --> 00:40:29,915
and you're gonna lose a sense of absorption

731
00:40:29,915 --> 00:40:32,937
and you will not be able to create empathetic immersion.

732
00:40:32,937 --> 00:40:32,977
So,

733
00:40:34,174 --> 00:40:36,055
Find a good cadence with your level designers

734
00:40:36,055 --> 00:40:38,116
and your concept artists and your level artists

735
00:40:38,116 --> 00:40:40,737
and see if you can find a way to roughly thumb out

736
00:40:40,737 --> 00:40:43,298
areas that will give you what you need in order

737
00:40:43,298 --> 00:40:46,359
to drive your scenes forward without pushing

738
00:40:46,359 --> 00:40:48,120
the production timeline beyond what it can go.

739
00:40:48,120 --> 00:40:55,063
The bottom line is, if you really bust your butt

740
00:40:55,063 --> 00:40:58,644
and work like crazy and it looks like you've done nothing

741
00:40:58,644 --> 00:41:01,265
and things look completely natural, you're onto something.

742
00:41:04,665 --> 00:41:08,207
So how to take this whole thing and work with the actors.

743
00:41:08,207 --> 00:41:10,768
Rehearsal was key for us.

744
00:41:10,768 --> 00:41:12,189
Actors already have a lot on their minds.

745
00:41:12,189 --> 00:41:14,090
They have to find the character,

746
00:41:14,090 --> 00:41:15,871
they have to memorize their lines,

747
00:41:15,871 --> 00:41:18,432
especially in a one-er because in a one-er,

748
00:41:18,432 --> 00:41:21,333
they have to memorize all their lines for the scene.

749
00:41:21,333 --> 00:41:22,474
It's not per cut and not per shot.

750
00:41:22,474 --> 00:41:25,615
So if they now have to memorize the choreography

751
00:41:25,615 --> 00:41:28,617
of what they need to be doing on top of their lines

752
00:41:28,617 --> 00:41:29,597
and trying to perform,

753
00:41:29,597 --> 00:41:31,758
you're not gonna get a good performance out of them.

754
00:41:32,690 --> 00:41:39,756
So incorporating that rehearsal and trying to get them to incorporate the ballet

755
00:41:39,756 --> 00:41:44,880
was very comfortable for them to then take that information on set and focus on acting.

756
00:41:44,880 --> 00:41:48,964
As the shot designer, you have to always keep in mind

757
00:41:48,964 --> 00:41:55,029
that you want to give your actors the freedom to perform and surprise you on set.

758
00:41:55,029 --> 00:42:00,693
